task-audortho_bold.json.Instructions: Spelling task: Determine if two words have same first vowel and following letters. Tone task: Determine if two tones are the same. Respond as quickly and accurately as possible. Please keep head still.
task-audortho_bold.json.TaskDescription: Participants were presented with 50 spelling judgement trials and 50 perceptual control tone judgement trials arranged into alternating 10 trial blocks, beginning with a spelling block. A 4000 ms instructions screen was presented at the beginning of each block which contained one word indicating the type of judgment, spelling or tones. In each trial three auditory stimuli were presented sequentially, each accompanied by a white fixation cross against a black background for 1000 ms. Following the third stimuli a yellow fixation cross was presented to indicate that the participants should make a response. The yellow fixation cross was presented for 1930 ms in spelling trials and for 1850 ms in control trials. Participants could make a response from the beginning of the third stimulus until the end of the trial. In spelling trials, stimuli consisted of three English words and participants were asked to judge whether the final word matched one of the first two words in rime, that is, had the same letters from the first vowel onwards. 15 of the 50 spelling trials contained matches and of these, 7 contained matches between the first and third stimulus, and 8 contained matches between the second and third stimulus. In matched trials the matching words were both orthographically and phonologically similar (O+P+), meaning they both matched in rime and rhyme. 15 of the 50 non-match trials contained two words that rhymed but did not match in spelling, denoted orthographically dissimilar but phonologically similar (O-P+). The remaining 20 trials were both orthographically and phonologically dissimilar (O-P-). In perceptual control tone trials, participants were presented with three pure tones which were either high (700 Hz), medium (500 Hz) or low (300 Hz) frequency. Each tone was 600 ms in duration and contained a 100 ms linear fade in and fade out. 30 of the 50 control trials contained a matching tone pair with 15 of those being a match between the first and third stimuli and 15 being a match between the second and third stimuli. Trials were pseudo-randomly assigned to blocks and all participants completed trials and blocks in the same fixed order. Each task lasted approximately 9 minutes. All lexical auditory stimuli were recorded by a native Chicagoan female voice in a soundproof booth with a digital recorder and a high-quality microphone. Words longer than 800 ms were shorted through linear transformation to 800 ms. All words were normalized in amplitude.

task-audsynt_bold.json.Instructions: Grammar task: Determine if words are grammatical. Tone task: Determine if two tones are the same. Respond as quickly and accurately as possible. Please keep head still.
task-audsynt_bold.json.TaskDescription: Participants were presented with 50 grammar judgement trials and 50 perceptual control tone judgement trials arranged into alternating 10 trial blocks, beginning with a grammar block. A 4000 ms instructions screen was presented at the beginning of each block which contained one word indicating the type of judgment, grammar or tones. In each trial three auditory stimuli were presented sequentially, each accompanied by a white fixation cross against a black background for 1000 ms. The yellow fixation cross was presented for 1930 ms in grammar trials and for 1850 ms in control trials. Participants could make a response from the beginning of the third stimulus until the end of the trial. In grammar trials, stimuli consisted of three English words and participants were asked to judge whether the phrase that the three words made was grammatical (e.g. ducks are quacking). 30 of the 50 grammar trials were grammatical. The remaining 20 trials contained a grammar violation and were labelled ungrammatical. In perceptual control tone trials, participants were presented with three pure tones which were either high (700 Hz), medium (500 Hz) or low (300 Hz) frequency. Each tone was 600 ms in duration and contained a 100 ms linear fade in and fade out. 30 of the 50 control trials contained a matching tone pair with 15 of those being a match between the first and third stimuli and 15 being a match between the second and third stimuli. Trials were pseudo-randomly assigned to blocks and all participants completed trials and blocks in the same fixed order. Each task lasted approximately 9 minutes. All lexical auditory stimuli were recorded by a native Chicagoan female voice in a soundproof booth with a digital recorder and a high-quality microphone. Words longer than 800 ms were shorted through linear transformation to 800 ms. All words were normalized in amplitude.

README:
#Description

This dataset contains functional MRI data while participants ages 9-35 complete auditory and visual spelling, rhyming, meaning, and syntactic judgement tasks. All tasks were presented using PsyScope. In addition this dataset contains standardized testing data from pediatric participants on the Comprehensive Test of Phonological Processing (CTOPP), the Peabody Picture Vocabulary Test - Third Edition (PPVT-IIII), the Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children - Third Edition (WISC-III), the Woodcock Johnson - Third Edition (WJ-III), and the Wide Range Achievement Test - Third Edition (WRAT-III). See data dictionary json files for task and test descriptions.

#Acq

Acq-a,b,c indicate the visit day that tasks were completed. Corresponding shifted aquisition dates can be found in the participants.tsv. These were not separated into different session folders as they were not considered to be separate for analysis and often T1w anatomical images were not collected at all visits.

#Defacing

All SPGR anatomical files were defaced using pydeface

# Known Issues

Images were converted from img and hdr files using mri_convert with default settings as orientation files were not present
